<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-254-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 254 928.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  March 1990 v9 n6 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How CD-ROM has made two high school libraries vibrant informationcenters.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mendrinos, Roxanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two high schools (HS) are using different approaches to expandstudents' use of CD-ROM information storage and retrieval systems.andO;Because the ability to locate, retrieve and use information isconsidered an indispensable skill for all high school students,Lewiston HS in Maine first introduced teachers to the technologyand databases available via the school's five microcomputers andCD-ROM systems.andP;  The teachers in turn incorporated student use ofthe CD-ROM databases into English and social studies classes.andO;Queen Anne's County HS in Maryland integrates CD-ROM software intoits 140 microcomputer network to provide access for students andteachers without their being in the library media center.andP;  Classesin research are part of the curriculum and in an additionalinnovation students are being encouraged to access the informationdatabases from home.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CD-ROMInformation Storage and RetrievalEducationSecondary SchoolsLibraries.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Sources of additional information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>